# Cursor Compatibility Principles

## 1. Use Cursor Rules Instead of Claude Sub-Agents

Claude uses sub-agents such as:

- `analyze-requirements`
- `write-test-cases`
- `generate-edge-cases`
- `execute-tests`
- `classify-severity`
- `report-bug`
- `review-test-cases`
- `report-session`

In Cursor, coordinate the equivalent `.mdc` rules:

```text
.cursor/rules/
├── 00-global-qa.mdc
├── 01-analyze-requirements.mdc
├── 02-parse-criteria.mdc
├── 03-write-test-cases.mdc
├── 04-edge-cases.mdc
├── 05-review-test-cases.mdc
├── 06-execute-tests.mdc
├── 07-exploratory-testing.mdc
├── 08-bug-reporting.mdc
├── 09-session-report.mdc
└── 10-severity-classification.mdc
```

When a workflow says "run a rule", apply the behavior defined by that rule. Do not reference Claude agent invocation.

## 2. Use Repository Context First

Before producing QA artifacts, inspect available code and project files.

Prioritize:

- requirements
- Jira ticket content
- acceptance criteria
- repository implementation
- validation rules
- database schema
- existing automated tests
- knowledge-base facts
- UI screenshots or app URL observations

When documentation and implementation conflict, flag the mismatch.

## 3. Use MCP Tools When Available

Cursor may have MCP servers configured for:

- Playwright
- Qase
- Jira
- database or filesystem helpers

Use MCP tools when available.

If an MCP tool is unavailable:

- do not claim the action was completed externally
- produce a local artifact or action checklist instead
- clearly state what must be done manually
- continue the workflow when useful

Do not manually start or stop MCP servers from this rule.

## 4. Do Not Claim External Side Effects Without Confirmation

Never claim that you:

- created Qase test cases
- updated Qase results
- closed a Qase run
- created Jira issues
- linked Jira issues to Qase
- uploaded attachments
- updated a remote sprint
- changed a remote ticket

unless the tool call succeeded or the user explicitly confirms it was done.

## 5. Preserve Local Artifacts

Use this standard folder:

```text
qa-artifacts/
├── screenshots/
├── console-logs/
├── network-logs/
├── traces/
├── downloads/
├── db-validation/
├── bugs/
├── reports/
└── session-report.md
```

When an external system is unavailable, local artifacts are the source of truth.

